WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.260
One of the challenges that we've seen time and time again is that there's often a gap

00:00:12.260 --> 00:00:18.040
between data scientists and those stakeholders they're hoping to inform. And that gap a lot

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:23.440
of times is the result of different mediums. And so that creates a problem for us is that

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:28.559
if we just wait for decision makers to proactively go visit our work, we're not actually closing

00:00:28.559 --> 00:00:33.599
that gap. But that's one problem. We also see something else kind of interesting happen

00:00:33.599 --> 00:00:40.759
as data science teams try to close this gap. And so one thing, as we said, is that maybe

00:00:40.759 --> 00:00:45.959
the dashboards fall by the wayside. Another thing that can often happen is that stakeholders

00:00:45.959 --> 00:00:50.720
will get excited. They'll say, great, this insight makes sense. Can you bring it to my

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:57.400
medium? Can you copy and paste those predictions into my spreadsheet? Or can you send me a

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:02.320
screenshot of that plot so I can put it in my presentation? And that leads to a lot

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:09.120
of painful, labor-intensive work. But I'd like to propose for you today an alternative,

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:14.360
a solution that we've found a lot of success using ourselves here at RStudio. And so what

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:19.080
does this solution entail? Instead of creating a dashboard, what we like to do is create

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:26.080
a proactive notifier or something that is going to alert me to the information that

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:30.839
I need to know. And in our case, we spend most of our time inside of our inboxes. So

00:01:30.839 --> 00:01:34.519
that's where our alerts go is through email. And so that's what we're going to talk about

00:01:34.519 --> 00:01:42.720
today is how you can use a rich set of R packages to allow you to create these proactive notifications.

00:01:42.720 --> 00:01:46.639
Oftentimes these notifications need to meet the expectations of our stakeholders for how

00:01:46.639 --> 00:01:51.779
they're formatted. So we'll look at some new packages that are available to help you precisely

00:01:51.779 --> 00:01:56.260
format these results. And then finally, we don't want to solve this dashboard fatigue

00:01:56.260 --> 00:02:00.900
problem by introducing another type of fatigue, which would be email fatigue. And so we're

00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:05.900
going to talk about how you can only send these alerts on conditions so that instead

00:02:05.900 --> 00:02:10.940
of sending emails every day, you can send emails more specifically when there's a problem

00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:14.100
at hand. We also don't want to introduce data science fatigue. So we're going to talk about

00:02:14.100 --> 00:02:18.619
how we can achieve these proactive notifications in an automated way. The picture that you're

00:02:18.619 --> 00:02:24.500
seeing here is one of my favorite examples of this workflow. One of my roles at RStudio

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:30.100
is to keep track of all the different R packages that we build and maintain. For some of you

00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:35.279
on the line, R packages might be a newer thing. So briefly, they're sort of the bread and

00:02:35.279 --> 00:02:39.779
butter of how data science gets done in R. They're also one of the main things that we're

00:02:39.779 --> 00:02:44.660
responsible for at RStudio is creating these different R packages. And so every day, we

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:51.740
go and we build all of these packages. And we want to know if any of those builds fail,

00:02:51.740 --> 00:02:57.100
especially if it's a really popular package. We don't want to get a whole bunch of emails

00:02:57.100 --> 00:03:01.300
from users saying, hey, this package isn't available or doesn't work. We kind of want

00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:05.860
to stay ahead of those types of problems. And so what a data scientist named Greg and

00:03:05.860 --> 00:03:10.820
I came up with is this workflow where every day we run these builds. And then if there's

00:03:10.820 --> 00:03:15.779
a problem, and critically, only if there's a problem, do we get these types of targeted

00:03:15.779 --> 00:03:21.539
emails that tell me exactly what the problem was and allow me to then take further action.

00:03:21.539 --> 00:03:25.500
We're not the only ones who are kind of using this pattern successfully. So I just want

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:30.940
to tell you a few quick stories before we get into the weeds of writing the code. One

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:37.539
of my favorite stories is from a large infrastructure as a service provider, so a company that maintains

00:03:37.539 --> 00:03:43.580
thousands, if not hundreds of thousands of servers. And what they use this workflow to

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:49.979
do was track their hardware uptime. And then if they saw a problem arising, they could

00:03:49.979 --> 00:03:55.020
send a proactive alert out to their vendors in the context of their support level agreement

00:03:55.020 --> 00:04:00.699
or SLA. And what this team was really excited about is before adopting this workflow, they

00:04:00.699 --> 00:04:06.259
had done this type of task in JIRA. And any time they onboarded a new vendor or they modified

00:04:06.259 --> 00:04:11.339
their SLA, they had to manually click through a whole bunch of steps in JIRA to accomplish

00:04:11.339 --> 00:04:16.940
this task. The great thing about this workflow is that it's all based on code. So it's really

00:04:16.940 --> 00:04:22.019
easy to reuse these different rules and different R Markdown documents that you're going to

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:27.339
write. And so this allowed the team to easily cut down their onboarding time.

00:04:27.339 --> 00:04:33.260
Another really awesome story of this type of technology applied was in a high-tech manufacturer

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:37.059
called People Ops Department, so kind of an HR group. And they had this challenging

00:04:37.059 --> 00:04:43.260
task where they needed to notify division managers about employee overtime problems.

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:47.619
So say an employee worked more overtime than they were allowed, they wanted to send out

00:04:47.619 --> 00:04:53.100
an alert. And before, they had a dashboard. And what they found was there are 30 different

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:58.220
division managers were not reliably going to that dashboard every day to check if there

00:04:58.220 --> 00:05:04.179
was problems. And so they adopted this workflow to instead send out an email to a manager

00:05:04.179 --> 00:05:09.140
only if there was actually a problem with a specific employee's overtime submission.

00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:13.899
And they actually won an award of excellence for adopting this workflow, which I think

00:05:13.899 --> 00:05:18.660
is really exciting because it's ultimately a pretty simple concept that we're talking

00:05:18.660 --> 00:05:22.859
about here. And so if they're able to win excellence awards, I think that's going to

00:05:22.859 --> 00:05:27.660
be accessible to a lot of teams as well.

